c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 23.319, 21.284, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>middle</i> <b>ὄλλυμαι</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 20.21, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 179 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>imperfect</i> ὠλλύμην [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “El.” 927, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Alcestis” 633: \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<i>future</i> ὀλέομαι, -οῦμαι, <i>2nd pers.</i> <i>plural</i> ὀλέεσθε [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 21.133 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; but <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>singular</i> ὀλεῖται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2.325: \">Refs</a>]<i>aorist 2</i> ὠλόμην, <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>singular</i> ὤλετο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 13.772, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 565 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>], etc.; <i>Ionic dialect</i> ὀλέσκετο (ἀπ- [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 11.586) \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>participle</i> ὀλόμενος as <i>adjective</i>, see at {οὐλόμενος}: <i>perfect</i> ὄλωλα, see [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Bacchylides Lyricus 111\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>pluperfect</i> ὀλώλειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 10.187:\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] — <i>passive</i>, <i>aorist</i> ὀλεσθῆναι, <i>future</i> ὀλεσθήσομαι (ἀπ-), [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" LXX.Psa.82(83).17, 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 9.728.—The simple Verb only poetical and later Prose, as LXX, ἀπόλλυμι being used in Comedy texts and Classical Prose. \">LXX+2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level1><b>__A</b></Level1> <i>active</i>: <br /><Level2><b>__I</b></Level2> <b>destroy, make an end of,</b> and of living beings, <b>kill,</b> νῆάς τ᾽ ὀλέσας καὶ πάντας Ἀχαιούς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 8.498, compare 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 23.319; γένος ὀλέσσαι.. θανάτῳ 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 3.41; ρένος ὠλέσατε πρυμνόθεν 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Septem contra Thebas” 1061 (_anapaest meter_); θανεῖται καὶ θανοῦσ᾽ ὀλεῖ τινα 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 751; ὀλεῖ ὀλεῖ με 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Andromache” 856 (Lyric poetry) \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἁ φιλοχρηματία Σπάρταν ὀλεῖ, ἄλλο γὰρ οὐδέν Oracle texts cited in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Fragmenta” 544 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; also, of <b>doing away with</b> evil, νῆστιν ὤλεσεν νόσον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1017 (Lyric poetry). \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>lose,</b> μένος, θυμόν, ψυχήν, ἦτορ ὀλέσαι, <b>lose life, die,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 8.358, 13.763, 5.250; πόνον ὀρταλίχων ὀλέσαντες 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 54 (_anapaest meter_); ἄγραν ὤλεσα [prev. author] “Eu.” 148 (Lyric poetry); τᾶς ἀνάνδρου κοίτας ὀλέσασα λέκτρον 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Medea” 436 (Lyric poetry). \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level1><b>__B</b></Level1> <i>middle</i>, <br /><Level2><b>__B.I</b></Level2> <b>perish, come to an end,</b> and of living beings, <b>die,</b> especially a violent death, ἀπ᾽ αἰῶνος νέος ὤλεο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 24.725; ὤλεθ᾽ ὑπ᾽ Αἰγίσθοιο δόλῳ 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 3.235; δόλοις ὀλούμεθ᾽ 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 888; ἦέ τις ὤλετ᾽ ὀλέθρῳ 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 4.489: with _accusative_ _cognate_, κακὸν οἶτον ὄληαι, ὀλέεσθε κακὸν μόρον, 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 3.417, 21.133; θάνατον “Anthologia Graeca” 7.745 (Antip. Sid.) \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὄλοιο, ὄλοισθε, <b>may'st thou, may ye perish !</b> a form of cursing very common in Trag., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 961, 1019, 1285, etc.; so ὀλοίμην [prev. author] “OT” 645; ὄλοιτο [prev. work] 1349 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], etc.; ὄλοιντο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Tr.” 383:— 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] has <i>active</i> and <i>middle</i> in emphatic contrast, ὀλλύντων τε καὶ ὀλλυμένων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 4.451, 8.65, compare 11.83. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__B.II</b></Level2> of things, <b>to be lost,</b> μή τί μοι ἐκ μεγάρων κειμήλιον.. ὄληται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 15.91; ὤλετό μοι νόστος 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 9.413, compare 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 1.168; κλέος 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 9.415, compare 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 918. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__B.III</b></Level2> <i>perfect</i> ὄλωλα (Syrac. ὀλώλω, Hilgard <b>Exc.ex Hdn.</b>[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" p.30), \">Refs</a>]<b>to have perished, to be dead, undone, ruined,</b> ὄλωλε μάχῃ ἔνι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 15.111, +others, compare 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Persae” 255, 1016 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], etc.; τῶν ὀλωλότων of the <b>dead,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Ag.” 346, compare 672, 1367, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 174 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: also of things, <b>to be in a state of ruin,</b> ἐσθίεταί μοι οἶκος, ὄλωλε δὲ πίονα ἔργα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 4.318. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G8491","accentedUnicode":"ὄλλυμι","shortDef":"to destroy","mediumDef":"to destroy","stepGloss":"to destroy","stepTransliteration":"ollumi",